article.description: Reserve Laurie Koehn scored 15 points, shooting 5-for-7 on 3-pointers, and the Mystics beat the Shock 76-67 Saturday in the regular season finale for both teams.
article.headline: Mystics finish off season with win over Shock
article.linkText: Mystics finish off season with win over Shock
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reserve Laurie Koehn scored 15 points,
shooting 5-for-7 on 3-pointers, and the Washington Mystics beat the
Detroit Shock 76-67 Saturday in the regular season finale for both
teams.

The game had little meaning as Washington (16-18) was eliminated
from playoff contention with a loss at Connecticut the previous
night. Though the teams finished tied and split four meetings,
Detroit (16-18) earned the fourth and final Eastern Conference
playoff spot because of a better conference record.

The Shock starts postseason play Wednesday against the
first-place Sun, and Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer went with his
usual bench players throughout the game. Still, the Shock stayed
close until Koehn and Temeka Johnson sparked a 15-point run in the
second half.

"I didn't want to get somebody hurt in a meaningless game,"
Laimbeer said. "We have a good bench, and they played hard."

Koehn made two 3s, and Johnson hit two jumpers and had some key
passes during the stretch that gave the Mystics a 67-51 lead with
just under 9 minutes left.

"This was a very difficult game for our players," Washington
coach Richie Adubato said. "We had to finish this season the way
we played this season. We always gave it 110 percent."

Washington shot 10-for-26 on 3s, while Detroit was 0-for-5.

Johnson had 10 points and five assists, and DeLisha Milton-Jones
added 15 points, eight rebounds and seven assists. Alana Beard had
13 points and seven assists.

Reserve Plenette Pierson scored a game-high 20 points for the
Shock. She made 12 of 19 free throws for Detroit, which went to the
line 38 times -- compared to just 12 for the Mystics.
